<div id="p120" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#28&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=120#p120">2008-03-24 03:13:36</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89643">Himaatin</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>Which, again, will not happen for several years. Earliest projected date of v4 depletion is 2011 to my knowledge. And btw, i did not say that ipv6-only is not relevant in general, i'm only saying that v4+v6 will be here much sooner than the latter.</p></div></blockquote><p>There ARE already people, who have IPv6-only connections. It's not a matter of the future. Just because the majority still has IPv4 (only or dual-stack) it doesn't mean, that the others can be ignored.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>This means the nodes will be v4 in reality but speak v6 via tunneling, so they'll contact the trackers via v4 for example.</p></div></blockquote><p>But they could connect it via IPv6 (tunnel) as well, if they'd like to.<br />It's not that they shouldn't be able to use IPv6 connections, but like I said IMHO it's not the job of an IPv4-only tracker to help them find IPv6-peers (or vice-versa), but the peers should care about it themselves.<br /><br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>As i said, v4-trackers handing out v6-addresses is a real scenario and it already works... so why are we still discussing this?</p></div></blockquote><p>Well, if I understood it correct, then this site/forum is meant to devise protocol standards and policies. If you'd just say &quot;it works, so it's okay&quot;, this site wouldn't be needed in the first place. Standards usually have to be based on a lot of thoughts, making sense. Not everything that &quot;already works&quot; is fit to be put into an official standard, and a tracker, that hands out contact information for protocols it doesn't understand itself just doesn't make sense. (IMHO)</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
