<div id="p139" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#31&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=139#p139">2008-03-29 12:55:38</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89643">Himaatin</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>I agree that a tracker listening on a v6 interface is preferable, but just updating the software to do a few checks is far more realistic than convincing the hoster to run v6 for you.</p></div></blockquote><p>Well, if your premise is &quot;Come hell or high water, I need to provide tracking for IPv6-clients&quot;, then it definately is more realistic.<br />My thought is just: &quot;It the machine, hosting the tracker has IPv6, then it may track IPv6-clients, if not then not&quot;.<br /><br />You may see it from an economic point of view: If IPv4-only connected machines are able to track IPv6-clients, then there won't be much changes in the market. But if it requires an IPv6-capable machine to track IPv6 clients, this opens up the possibilities of a new generation of tracker-providers to compete with PirateBay&amp;Co.&nbsp; ;-)<br /><br /><br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>yeah, but a significant proportion of the ipv6-using-v4-announces will probably be using teredo or 6to4.</p></div></blockquote><p>I don't think so. Teredo, 6to4 and other tunnel-connections are the present solution. It's for geeks and IPv6-developers, but far too complicated for the average user.<br />If IPv6 is becoming widely used, then it will be through native connections, which will work out of the box.<br /><br /><br />BTW, why is there no standard-document for the scrape-page? Shouldn't there be one for this?<br /><br />IIRC a scrape response contains the keys complete, incomplete and downloaded. I think the IPv6-tracker-standard should contain a paragraph, concerning the scrape-page. A tracker that tracks IPv4 and IPv6 clients should add the keys complete_ipv4, complete_ipv6, incomplete_ipv4 and incomplete_ipv6.<br />For a tracker that tracks just one protocol this isn't necessary, but for hybrid trackers it could be advantageous to know how many clients of a specific protocol there are, and since there are hybrid clients it requires three values (i.e. complete_ipv4 + complete_ipv6 &gt; complete).</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<div id="p140" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#32&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=140#p140">2008-03-29 14:14:51</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89618">The 8472</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Azureus Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>My thought is just: &quot;It the machine, hosting the tracker has IPv6, then it may track IPv6-clients, if not then not&quot;.</p></div></blockquote><p>i do not see the point in artificially restricting ipv6 client support to ipv6 trackers, there is no advantage (for bittorrent) in this.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>But if it requires an IPv6-capable machine to track IPv6 clients, this opens up the possibilities of a new generation of tracker-providers to compete with PirateBay&amp;Co.&nbsp; ;-)</p></div></blockquote><p>political-economical motivations should play no part in a technical standards-making process apart from overall efficiency.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>BTW, why is there no standard-document for the scrape-page? Shouldn't there be one for this?</p></div></blockquote><p>imo the overall stats should not distinguish between ipv4 and ipv6 as they give an overview of the overall swarm conditions, since at least partial ipv4 and v6 interconnectivity is to be expected for the next few years a combined overview should provide sufficiently accurate stats to judge swarm health and adjust queue rules... let's not overdesign it.</p>
					<p class="postedit"><em>Last edited by The 8472 (2008-03-29 14:15:58)</em></p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Az dev</div>
