<div id="p142" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#34&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=142#p142">2008-03-30 05:15:48</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89643">Himaatin</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>i do not see the point in artificially restricting ipv6 client support to ipv6 trackers, there is no advantage (for bittorrent) in this.</p></div></blockquote><p>But there isn't a disadvantage neither... and I don't see any advantages in doing otherwise.<br />It's more complicated to implement, can be exploited more easily and its also a hindrance for the spread of IPv6.<br /><br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>imo the overall stats should not distinguish between ipv4 and ipv6 as they give an overview of the overall swarm conditions, since at least partial ipv4 and v6 interconnectivity is to be expected for the next few years a combined overview should provide sufficiently accurate stats to judge swarm health and adjust queue rules... let's not overdesign it.</p></div></blockquote><p>IMHO this is an important information, that should be available. Just imagine you are connecting to a swarm which is supposed to have thousands of participants, but you don't get any connection, since you can't see, that you are the only IPv4-only client, while everyone else is IPv6-only.<br />Besides: Technically speaking this are two different swarms, which just overlap each other.<br /><br />And it shouldn't really be more work to implement it, since it's information the tracker should keep anyways.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
